  <hr /><a name="dimensions"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DIMENSIONS </dt>
  <dd>The actual measured size of a flag, or of a charge thereon, as opposed to its proportions (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp8.html#proportions">proportions</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr1.html#rectangle">rectangle</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#specification">specification</a>&rsquo;, and
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#specificationsheet">specification sheet</a>&rsquo;,).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d112.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d112.gif" border="0" alt="example of dimensions" height="108" /></a>
  <hr /><a name="dimidiated"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DIMIDIATED </dt>
  <dd>(adj) The heraldic term for a charge or charges, such as animals, birds (particularly eagles) or fleur-de-lis, 
  forming part of a coat of arms, or an entire coat of arms as defined herein, which are halved along the vertical 
  centre line of a shield, banner of arms or a flag &ndash; but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc7.html#conjoinedflag">conjoined</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#demi">demi</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc4.html#coatofarms">coat of arms 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#entire">entire 1)</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-i.html#impale">impale</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d115.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d115.gif" alt="[dimidiated flags]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4581.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4581.gif" alt="[dimidiated flags]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1570.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1570.gif" alt="[dimidated flags]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag of </em> <a href="pl-op-ny.html"><em>Nysa</em></a><em>, Poland (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="ch-ge.html">Geneva</a>, Switzerland (fotw); 
  Flag of the <a href="gb-cinq.html">Cinque Ports</a>, UK (fotw) </em>  
  <p><em>Please note, however, that where two sets of dimidiated arms or any 
  elements thereof are set side by side in heraldic terms they are said to be 
  &lsquo;impaled by dimidiation&rsquo;, and that (whilst this is often the case) one dimidiated charge, or set of 
  dimidiated arms, need not necessarily be set beside another so 
  halved (as per the example shown above) &ndash; see &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dve2.html#entire"><em>entire 1)</em></a><em>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dvc7.html#conjoined"><em>conjoined</em></a><em>&rsquo;). </em>
  </dd>
  
  </p>
  
  <hr /><a name="dimidiation"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DIMIDIATION</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="#dimidiated">dimidiated</a>&rsquo; and following note above.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2287a.gif">
